IMPORTS of goods and services rose by 41.2 per cent to 12,552.7 million US dollars in the year ending February this year. Much of the increase was in intermediate and consumer goods, particularly white petroleum products and pharmaceutical products. Oil refined white petroleum products) imports increased by 99.3 percent to 2,119.0 million US dollars owing to both price and volume effects. Services payments amounted to 1,953.7 million US dollars from 1,169.2 million US dollars in the year ending February last year largely emanating from freight payments consistent with the surge in import bill. The primary income account recorded a deficit of 954.3 million US dollars in the year ending February up from 873.4 million US dollars in 2021 due to a rise in interest payments abroad. On a monthly basis, a deficit of 105.8 million US dollars was recorded compared to 59.7 million US dollars in February last year. The secondary income account surplus rose to 587.2 million US dollars in the year ending February compared with 407.6 million US dollars in the corresponding period last year due to a rise in private transfers. On monthly basis, a surplus of 50.8 million US dollars was recorded in February higher than 29.2 million US dollars in February last year. Month-on-month, services payments increased to 222.4 million US dollars in February this year from 104 million US dollars in February last year mainly driven by freight payments.